One thing I’d be careful about—and I think you’ve already intuited this—is that every acorn needs the right soil.

A cue that perfectly reconstructs an idea for you might mean nothing to someone encountering it for the first time.

So there are really three levels:

1. Private seeds — only you can regrow them.
2. Shared seeds — your collaborators can regrow them.
3. Universal seeds — almost anyone can regrow them with enough patience.

Moving ideas from level 1 to level 3 is a kind of translation. That’s one of the hardest problems in teaching, writing, and communication.

And perhaps that’s why your detective analogy fits so well.

The best mysteries don’t tell the audience the answer.

They leave just enough clues that, when the reveal comes, people think:

“Of course. It was there the whole time.”

That’s faithful reconstruction.

Not because the information was hidden.

Because the capacity to see it had to develop first.